SIMPLE: traffic
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Traffic
<hw>Traf"fic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Trafficked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Trafficking</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>trafiquer</ets>; cf. It. <ets>trafficare</ets>, Sp.
<ets>traficar</ets>, <ets>trafagar</ets>, Pg. <ets>traficar</ets>,
<ets>trafegar</ets>, <ets>trafeguear</ets>, LL. <ets>traficare</ets>; of
uncertain origin, perhaps fr. L. <ets>trans</ets> across, over +
<ets>-ficare</ets> to make (see <er>-fy</er>, and cf. G.
<ets>⟦uum⟧bermachen</ets> to transmit, send over, e. g., money, wares);
or cf. Pg. <ets>trasfegar</ets> to pour out from one vessel into
another, OPg. also, to traffic, perhaps fr. (assumed) LL.
<ets>vicare</ets> to exchange, from L. <ets>vicis</ets> change (cf.
<er>Vicar</er>).]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass goods and commodities
from one person to another for an equivalent in goods or money; to buy
or sell goods; to barter; to trade.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To trade meanly or mercenarily; to
bargain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Traffic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Traffic
<hw>Traf"fic</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To exchange in traffic; to
effect by a bargain or for a consideration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Traffic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Traffic
<hw>Traf"fic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>trafic</ets>, It.
<ets>traffico</ets>, Sp. <ets>tr⟦aacute⟧fico</ets>,
<ets>tr⟦aacute⟧fago</ets>, Pg. <ets>tr⟦aacute⟧fego</ets>, LL.
<ets>traficum</ets>, <ets>trafica</ets>. See <er>Traffic</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Commerce, either by barter or by
buying and selling; interchange of goods and commodities;
trade.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A merchant of great <qex>traffic</qex> through the world.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>traffic</qex> in honors, places, and pardons.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word, like <xex>trade</xex>, comprehends every
species of dealing in the exchange or passing of goods or merchandise
from hand to hand for an equivalent, unless the business of relating may
be excepted. It signifies appropriately foreign trade, but is not
limited to that.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1526 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Commodities of the market.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You 'll see a draggled damsel⟦br⟧
From Billingsgate her fishy <qex>traffic</qex> bear.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The business done upon a railway, steamboat line,
etc., with reference to the number of passengers or the amount of
freight carried.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Traffic return</b></col>, <cd>a periodical statement of
the receipts for goods and passengers, as on a railway line.</cd> --
<col><b>Traffic taker</b></col>, <cd>a computer of the returns of
traffic on a railway, steamboat line, etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trafficable</ent>⟦br⟧
